chordpro:
{title: O Sacred Head, Now Wounded}
{subtitle: Passion Chorale — Bach's harmonization, English tr. J.W. Alexander, 1830}
{key: Em}
{time: 4/4}
{tempo: 64}
{comment: Bach used this chorale 5 times in the St. Matthew Passion. The Latin original is from Bernard of Clairvaux (12th c.).}

{start_of_verse: 1}
[Em]O sacred [B7]Head, now [Em]wounded
[Am]With grief and [B7]shame weighed [Em]down
[Em]Now scornfully [B7]sur[Em]rounded
[Am]With thorns, Thine [B7]only [Em]crown
[G]O sacred [D]Head, what [G]glory
[Em]What bliss till [B7]now was [Em]Thine!
[Em]Yet, though des[B7]pised and [Em]gory
[Am]I joy to [B7]call Thee [Em]mine
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 2}
[Em]What Thou, my [B7]Lord, hast [Em]suffered
[Am]Was all for [B7]sinners' [Em]gain
[Em]Mine, mine was [B7]the trans[Em]gression
[Am]But Thine the [B7]deadly [Em]pain
[G]Lo, here I [D]fall, my [G]Saviour!
[Em]'Tis I de[B7]serve Thy [Em]place
[Em]Look on me [B7]with Thy [Em]favor
[Am]Vouchsafe to [B7]me Thy [Em]grace
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 3}
[Em]What language [B7]shall I [Em]borrow
[Am]To thank Thee, [B7]dearest [Em]Friend
[Em]For this Thy [B7]dying [Em]sorrow
[Am]Thy pity [B7]without [Em]end?
[G]O make me [D]Thine for[G]ever
[Em]And should I [B7]fainting [Em]be
[Em]Lord, let me [B7]never, [Em]never
[Am]Outlive my [B7]love to [Em]Thee
{end_of_verse}
